The absorption titration studies were performed to (i) interpret the excited-state reaction, and (ii) identify the type of interaction of DAN-GQD with FA and MeCob. The free FA and MeCob molecules shown the predominant absorption bands ca. at 276 and 353 nm, and 254 and 347 nm, respectively (Figure SI4A,B). In the absence of FA and MeCob, DAN-GQD (5 × 10−9 M) exhibits one distinct absorption band at 328 nm (π→π*) at in H2O (Figure SI5). The addition of FA (100 × 10-12 M; 0 - 1000 μL) gradually increases the intensity of absorption band, due to the static interaction and the formation of the ground-state complex with DAN-GQD [26], DAN-GQD∙FA, thus causing a redshift of about 12 nm (276 → 286 nm) in the absorption spectrum of FA (Fig. 3
                           ). In the current study, when the aqueous solution of MeCob (25 × 10-9 M; 0 – 1000 μL) was added to DAN-GQD, we observed strong redshift absorption bands (ca. 254 → 261 and 347 →350 nm) and a shoulder peak at 525 nm. The resultant multiple peaks with hyperchromic effect and isosbestic points (ca. 360, 475, and 550 nm) are may be due to the dynamic equilibrium existing between the large MeCob structure and DAN-GQD upon interaction [61] (Fig. 4
                           ).
